Dimensionality reduction (week 5)

Dimensionality reduction techniques allow us to simplify the interpretation of multidimensional data and models. These techniques include principal component analysis (PCA) and multiple correspondence analysis (MCA), which we will use to reduce multidimensional data to as few components as possible.

The human development and gender inequality data set (“human” data set) is created based on data from the United Nations Development Programme1. The R script create_human.R is used to generate the data. The original data sets (human development and gender inequality) consist of various indicators for different countries and regions around the world. These indicators can be used to assess the development of countries in a number areas, including economic, health, education and equality. The two data sets (human development and gender inequality) are joined together by country, while we also exclude undefined values and regions (including only countries). In the final data set, we have 155 rows and the 9 variables Country, Edu2.FM (female/male secondary education ratio), Labo.FM (female/male labour participation rate ratio), Edu.Exp (expected years of education), Life.Exp (life expectancy), GNI (gross national income per capita), Mat.Mor (maternal mortality rate), Ado.Birth (adolescent birth rate) and Parli.F (percent female representation in parliament). A summary of these variables is given in table (tab:sm5).

human <- read.csv("./data/human.csv")

# move country to rownames
human <- column_to_rownames(human, "Country")
# create summary table for data set
summary_table <- function(data, cap) {
  data_summary <- as.data.frame(apply(data, 2, summary))
  kable(data_summary, caption = cap, digits=2) %>%
  kable_styling(font_size = 12)
}

# make summary of human data set
summary_table(human, "Summary of human (development and gender inequality) data set.")

# plot histogram from vector
vhist <- function(var, xlab) ggplot() + aes(var) + 
  geom_histogram() + xlab(xlab) + ylab("Count")

# plot histograms for all variables in human data set
human_hist <- function(data) {
  h1 <- vhist(data$Edu2.FM, "Female/male secondary education ratio")
  h2 <- vhist(data$Labo.FM, "Female/male labour force participation ratio")
  h3 <- vhist(data$Edu.Exp, "Expected years of education")
  h4 <- vhist(data$Life.Exp, "Life expectancy")
  h5 <- vhist(data$GNI, "Gross national income per capita")
  h6 <- vhist(data$Mat.Mor, "Maternal mortality ratio")
  h7 <- vhist(data$Ado.Birth, "Adolescent birth rate")
  h8 <- vhist(data$Parli.F, "Female representation in parliament")
  
  grid.arrange(h1, h2, h3, h4, h5, h6, h7, h8, 
               ncol=4, nrow=2)
}

# plot histogram of variables
human_hist(human)

Histograms of values in human data set. 

human_cor <- cor(human) %>% round(digits = 2)

human_conf <- cor.mtest(human, conf.level = .95)
human_p <- human_conf$p
human_p[lower.tri(human_p, diag = T)] <- 1

corrplot.mixed(human_cor, 
         p.mat = human_p,
         upper = "circle",
         lower = "number",
         insig = "label_sig",
         pch.col = "black",
         pch.cex = 1.0,
         lower.col = "black",
         sig.level = c(.001, .01, .05))

Correlation matrix of human data set with correlation coefficients and \(p\)-values. 

human_pca <- prcomp(human)
biplot(human_pca, choices = 1:2)

tea <- read.csv("https://raw.githubusercontent.com/KimmoVehkalahti/Helsinki-Open-Data-Science/master/datasets/tea.csv", stringsAsFactors = TRUE)
View(tea)
tea <- dplyr::select(tea, c("Tea", "How", "sugar", "age_Q", "sex", "frequency", "SPC"))
tea_mca <- MCA(tea, graph = FALSE)
plot(tea_mca, invisible=c("ind"), graph.type = "classic", habillage = "quali")
